# Bulk edits: use a script in the terminal

When a change must touch **many files** and the transformation is **mechanical** (e.g. consistent find-and-replace, path or identifier renames, header updates), **implement it as a small script** (Python, PowerShell, or similar) and **run it in the terminal** instead of applying the same edit file-by-file in the editor.

## When this applies

- Same logical change repeated across a large set of paths (tens of files or huge diffs).
- Logic is easy to express in code: include/exclude globs, skip `data/` or binaries, skip vendor dirs, etc.

## When it does not need a script

- Only a **few** files, or the change needs **judgment per file** — direct edits are fine.

## How to run it

- Put one-off automation under **`scripts/`** (or a clearly named temp script) so it is visible in git history.
- Prefer a **dry-run** mode or print affected paths first, then run for real.
- After running, use **`git diff`** (or equivalent) to review the full change set.

This keeps large refactors auditable and avoids inconsistent partial application.
